<section id="broadcast" class="section-card">
    <h3 id="broadcast-block">Broadcast: The Declarative Bridge</h3>
    <p>
        Invoker Commands give HTML a declarative model for targeted commands (<code>commandfor</code>/<code>command</code>).
        But the platform has no declarative equivalent for broadcast commands. The
        <a href="/blocks/broadcast/">Broadcast</a> block fills this gap with a single attribute:
    </p>

    {% highlight "html" %}
<!-- Targeted: Invoker Commands (platform) -->
<button commandfor="panel-1" command="--view-show">Show</button>

<!-- Broadcast: Web Events (block) -->
<button broadcast="customEvents:close-modals">Close All Modals</button>
    {% endhighlight %}

    <p>
        On click, the <code>broadcast</code> behavior resolves the event class from the host element's injector scope,
        constructs an instance, and dispatches on <code>document</code>. Listeners using <code>listenForScoped</code>
        receive the event with full <code>instanceof</code> discrimination.
    </p>
</section>

<section id="ssr" class="section-card">
    <h3 id="ssr-contract">SSR Contract</h3>
    <p>
        This section defines the server-side rendering contract for <strong>Web Events</strong>.
        Event classes and dispatch logic are entirely client-side. The server's role is limited to
        preserving event-related attributes in the HTML output and ensuring the
        <a href="/projects/webbehaviors/#ssr">Web Behaviors</a> attribute passthrough contract is met.
    </p>

    <h4 id="ssr-server-output">Server Output Requirements</h4>
    <div class="comparison-table-wrapper mt-4">
        <table class="comparison-table">
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Feature</th>
                    <th>Server Output HTML</th>
                    <th>Notes</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Event attributes</strong></td>
                    <td>
<pre style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.8em;"><code>&lt;button on:click="save($event)"&gt;
  Save
&lt;/button&gt;</code></pre>
                    </td>
                    <td>Server MUST emit <code>on:*</code> attributes exactly as authored. This is a subset of the <a href="/projects/webbehaviors/#ssr">Web Behaviors</a> attribute passthrough contract.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Broadcast attributes</strong></td>
                    <td>
<pre style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.8em;"><code>&lt;button broadcast="customEvents:close-modals"&gt;
  Close All Modals
&lt;/button&gt;</code></pre>
                    </td>
                    <td>Server MUST emit <code>broadcast</code> attributes as-is. The value is an injector key referencing a scoped event class.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Event class registration</strong></td>
                    <td>No server output</td>
                    <td>Event classes (<code>customEvents:*</code> injector keys) are registered on the client. No serialization needed.</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
    </div>

    <h4 id="ssr-hydration-expectations">Client Hydration Expectations</h4>
    <ul class="list-disc ml-6 text-gray-600 text-sm">
        <li><strong>Attribute binding:</strong> <code>on:*</code> and <code>broadcast</code> attributes are processed by the <a href="/projects/webbehaviors/">Web Behaviors</a> system during DOM walk. Event listeners are attached at that point.</li>
        <li><strong>Event class resolution:</strong> The <code>broadcast</code> behavior resolves event classes from the injector scope at dispatch time, not at hydration time. No upfront resolution needed.</li>
        <li><strong>Listener registration:</strong> <code>listenForScoped()</code> calls register listeners that receive events with full <code>instanceof</code> discrimination. These are client-only registrations.</li>
    </ul>

    <h4 id="ssr-progressive-baseline">Progressive Enhancement Baseline</h4>
    <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">
        With zero JavaScript: <code>on:*</code> attributes are unknown to the browser and ignored.
        <code>broadcast</code> is an unknown attribute and ignored.
        Buttons and interactive elements retain their native behavior (form submission, navigation).
        No events are dispatched, but the page remains functional for its static content.
    </p>

    <h4 id="ssr-client-only">Client-Only Features</h4>
    <ul class="list-disc ml-6 text-gray-600 text-sm">
        <li><strong>Event dispatching:</strong> All <code>dispatchEvent()</code>, <code>broadcast</code>, and custom event construction</li>
        <li><strong>Scoped listeners:</strong> <code>listenForScoped()</code> with <code>instanceof</code> discrimination</li>
        <li><strong>Event class instantiation:</strong> <code>new CustomEvent()</code>, provider-based class resolution</li>
        <li><strong>Invoker Commands integration:</strong> <code>commandfor</code>/<code>command</code> attribute handling (platform feature)</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="comparison-block" style="background: rgba(251, 191, 36, 0.1); padding: 1.25rem; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #f59e0b; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
        <h4 id="ssr-implementor-note" style="margin-top: 0; color: #d97706; font-size: 1rem;">Implementor Note</h4>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
            This contract defines compliance requirements. The build system or server framework
            is responsible for preserving event attribute markup in the HTML output.
            Web Events does not ship an SSR runtime — it ships this specification.
            See also: <a href="/projects/webbehaviors/#ssr">Web Behaviors SSR Contract</a> for the full attribute passthrough specification.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<section id="research" class="section-card">
    <h3 id="research-link">Research</h3>
    <p>
        This project emerged from the <a href="/research/custom-events/">Custom Event Scoping &amp; Registry</a> research topic, which explores the full design space: Symbol-based events, protocol tags, scoped registries, and listener discrimination approaches. The research concluded that provider-based <code>instanceof</code> discrimination is the simplest primitive that covers all scenarios.
    </p>
</section>
